      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let me focus on the science.\n\nThe enzymatic breakdown of starches in sourdough starter involves several key players. The wild yeast, primarily Saccharomyces cerevisiae, produces enzymes such as amylase, which breaks down starches into simpler sugars like glucose and fructose. These sugars are then consumed by the yeast, producing ethanol and CO2 as byproducts.\n\nThe lactobacilli, on the other hand, produce enzymes like glucanase, which breaks down the cellulose and hemicellulose in the flour, releasing more sugars into the environment. These sugars are then consumed by the lactobacilli, producing lactic acid and other compounds that contribute to the sour flavor of sourdough.\n\nTemperature and hydration levels can affect the activity of these enzymes. For example, amylase activity is higher at temperatures between 20-30°C (68-86°F), while glucanase activity is more pronounced at lower temperatures. Hydration levels also impact the activity of these enzymes, with optimal activity typically occurring at around 60-70% water content.\n\nIn terms of the CO2 production, it's primarily driven by the yeast's fermentation",
      "source": "target",
